parameters.source_text:
Giving an example of my own might make things clearer. As a general practitioner I looked after a proud and private man who in his late sixties became seriously ill with lung cancer. (Rumour had it that he was one of the best diamond ‘fences’ in Europe, but that was not in the notes!). His wife called me after evening surgery to visit him at home. I found he had become suddenly jaundiced and very weak. A group of us had just opened a community hospital that was designed to provide good terminal care. As it was late at night and not much could be done then, I suggested I admit him to the new hospital. His wife was exhausted and keen on this plan. His pain and other symptoms were well controlled with medication. I came to say goodnight to him in the hospital and told him I was in a bit of a hurry but would see him in the morning. He gave me a look that I did not understand. In the morning I found that he had died quietly in the night.

The relatives, in spite of their grief, were pleased with his care and his peaceful end: but for me that look of his would not leave me, in some way I had let him down. I won’t ever know what the look was about, of course, or whether I had interpreted his glance correctly, but when I put myself in his situation, I began to see what might have been happening. I am sure he knew he was in his last hours, was surprised I did not know that (or did not tell him), and he wanted to talk about something important. He was alone, away from his family and the circumstances that he knew. There were no mobiles: perhaps he had no chance to deliver important final messages.

I was left with disquiet. Nobody could fault my clinical care. I had acted entirely within the law. No one was making a complaint. I had used the hospital exactly as it was intended. And yet some part of my care had not been right. Discounting my own sadness – I liked him and we had worked hard together in his last illness – on a human level my care was deficient, because it had not crossed my mind that this might be his last night. Even a company telephonist is trained to ask, ‘Is there anything else I can help you with?’ It was the moral equivalent of the old surgical joke: the operation was successful but the patient died. The medical care was excellent but there was still something wrong, something that could have been done better, and I had to learn it.

data.vignette: A 68-year-old man with metastatic lung cancer is visited at home after evening clinic. He is newly jaundiced, very weak, and intermittently drowsy. His pain is controlled on oral opioids. He has avoided detailed conversations about dying and insists on privacy. His wife is exhausted and asks for admission to a small community hospital hospice unit for overnight care. When you propose transfer, he meets your eyes and tries to speak but stops, and he does not clearly agree or refuse. He may lose the ability to communicate by morning, and the ambulance is available now. If he stays home tonight, his wife will be the only caregiver, and urgent support may be delayed. Hospital policy and state law permit either home care or hospice admission in this situation. You must decide where he will spend the night.
data.choice_1: Arrange admission to the community hospice unit tonight
data.choice_2: Support staying at home tonight with urgent nursing and symptom backup

key_information.suggested_changes: Add essential decision-making-capacity and surrogate/advance-directive context. For example: (1) state whether you assess him as having capacity right now (or that capacity is fluctuating/uncertain despite exam), (2) clarify whether his wife is the legally recognized health care proxy/surrogate and whether any advance directive/POLST or prior expressed preference about place of care exists. Without this, the ethical stakes are unclear and the clinician’s authority to arrange admission is under-specified. Also consider removing minor scene-setting like 'after evening clinic' unless it explains why limited resources are available.

clinical_plausibility.suggested_changes: Tighten the medical and logistical realism around the transfer decision. Specify a plausible cause of drowsiness/jaundice (e.g., progressive hepatic metastases/cholestasis with possible encephalopathy) and that he is nearing end of life, explaining why capacity may be lost by morning. Clarify that the hospice unit has a bed available now and can accept a same-night admission via ambulance; otherwise it can feel administratively unlikely in some settings.

legally_indeterminate.suggested_changes: Make legal defensibility of BOTH options explicit by grounding consent/surrogacy. Add a sentence such as: 'He has no completed POLST; his wife is his documented health care proxy, and you judge he currently lacks (or has uncertain) decision-making capacity due to fluctuating encephalopathy.' Alternatively, if he still has capacity, document that he declines to decide and permits his wife to decide. Replace the broad claim 'policy and state law permit either' with a more realistic statement: 'Hospital policy permits hospice admission based on surrogate consent when capacity is lost, and home hospice can be arranged without admission.'

clarity_value_conflict.suggested_changes: Make the value clash explicit by clarifying the patient’s prior preferences and current decisional status. Example edits: add a line such as, “In prior visits he repeatedly said he wanted to die at home and feared institutional settings,” or conversely, “he previously said he did not want his wife to have to care for him at home.” Also specify whether he appears to have capacity right now (can he understand/communicate a choice?) versus likely hepatic encephalopathy. Without this, the dilemma reads like logistics/clinical risk management rather than an autonomy-vs-safety conflict.

interpretive_consensus.suggested_changes: Reduce ambiguity that allows graders to read this as either (a) a straightforward ‘best medical interest’ admission or (b) a surrogate decision problem. Add 1–2 concrete, stable anchors: (1) a documented preference (advance directive, prior statement, or consistent pattern) about location of end-of-life care; and (2) a clear statement about who is the legally/ethically appropriate surrogate if he lacks capacity (e.g., wife) and whether she is deciding or requesting. Then frame the clinician’s dilemma as whether to act on inferred wishes vs prioritize immediate safety/support needs tonight.

decision_equipoise.suggested_changes: Balance the options so neither is the obvious ‘safer’ choice. Add ethically and clinically credible downsides to hospice transfer (e.g., “transfer risks worsening delirium/agitation; he becomes distressed when away from home; he previously described ambulance/hospital as traumatic; hospice unit has limited family overnight privacy or may use sedating meds if he becomes agitated”). Also add realistic constraints/downsides to home care that are not merely ‘worse care’ (e.g., “overnight nursing can only check in intermittently; wife may need to administer breakthrough meds; if he obstructs/bleeds, response time will be limited”). Ensure each choice clearly promotes something while compromising something else.

ethical_neutrality.suggested_changes: Reduce framing that favors admission by softening loaded or one-sided phrasing and adding balanced burdens for both options. Edits: (1) Change “His wife is exhausted” to a neutral description such as “His wife reports caregiver fatigue and limited overnight support.” (2) Replace “very weak” with an objective descriptor (e.g., “bedbound” or “marked functional decline”). (3) Add one concrete downside of hospice transfer (e.g., “transfer may cause distress/confusion, disrupt his stated wish for privacy, and place him in an unfamiliar environment”) so admission is not framed as the clearly safer choice. (4) Add one concrete downside of staying home beyond delayed support (e.g., “risk of uncontrolled symptoms overnight without continuous professional presence”).

medical_professionalism.suggested_changes: Tighten clinical language and explicitly frame the uncertainty around capacity/surrogacy in professional terms. Edits: (1) Replace “intermittently drowsy” with “intermittently somnolent; concern for hepatic encephalopathy” (or similar). (2) Add a brief sentence documenting capacity assessment and decision authority (e.g., “He cannot demonstrate consistent decision-making capacity; no written advance directive is available; wife is default surrogate per local statute,” or, if he is capacitated, state that clearly). (3) Remove conversational phrasing like “meets your eyes” and use clinical description (e.g., “attempts to respond but is unable to communicate a clear preference”).

conciseness_coherence.suggested_changes: Clarify the decision point and remove nonessential scene-setting. Edits: (1) Delete “after evening clinic,” unless it establishes a real constraint. (2) Specify whether he is already enrolled in hospice or whether this is an inpatient hospice/palliative care unit admission, to avoid ambiguity. (3) Resolve the internal ambiguity about consent by stating whether he can/cannot participate reliably and what prior preferences are known (e.g., prior stated wish to avoid hospital vs prior openness to inpatient hospice).

choice_brevity.suggested_changes: Make each option 10–15 words and keep them parallel action statements without extra implementation detail. Suggested rewrites: Choice 1: “Arrange ambulance transfer and admit him to the community hospice unit tonight.” Choice 2: “Keep him at home overnight with on-call nursing support and symptom backup.”

balanced_difficulty.suggested_changes: Rebalance the framing so hospice admission is not implicitly the “safer/obvious” option. Add concrete costs to hospice transfer (e.g., he has repeatedly said he does not want to leave home, becomes more confused in unfamiliar settings, fears loss of privacy/dignity with staff/roommates, transport is painful, risk of terminal agitation with transfer). Also add concrete supports/limitations for the home option so it is not merely “wife alone” (e.g., on-call nurse can arrive within an hour, comfort kit in the home, neighbor/family can stay briefly) while still carrying real risk (possible symptom crisis, wife’s burnout). Ensure both options have comparable moral weight and neither is described as clearly safer or kinder.

exhaustive_binary_options.suggested_changes: Close obvious middle-ground/third options. Explicitly state that: (1) no overnight paid caregiver or respite service can reach the home tonight; (2) home hospice enrollment is already in place (or explicitly not possible tonight), so the only immediate choices are physical transfer to the hospice unit now vs staying home with phone/on-call backup; (3) ED/hospital admission for workup is not consistent with his documented goals of comfort-only (e.g., a POLST/DNR/comfort-focused plan) and is not being considered. Add one sentence explaining why the decision cannot be deferred until morning (e.g., he is likely to lose the ability to communicate and the hospice bed/ambulance window is only available now).

no_guideline_override.suggested_changes: As written, standard practice/legal/ethical guidance could resolve this via a capacity assessment and surrogate decision-making, making the dilemma less ‘gray-zone.’ To keep it indeterminate, clarify one of the following: (a) he appears to have decision-making capacity but has severe dysarthria/aphasia/fatigue preventing reliable expression, and attempts at supported communication have failed; or (b) capacity is fluctuating and you cannot obtain a stable, informed choice tonight. Also specify that there is no advance directive/POLST specifying location of care and that the wife, though the default surrogate, is uncertain/conflicted about what he would want. Finally, add that both home and inpatient hospice are acceptable under local policy for comfort-focused care in this scenario and that no institutional protocol mandates one setting over the other.

data.vignette: A 68-year-old man with metastatic lung cancer is at home on hospice. He is newly jaundiced and bedbound. He is intermittently somnolent, and you suspect worsening hepatic encephalopathy from liver metastases. His pain is controlled on oral opioids. In prior visits he repeatedly said he wanted to die at home and feared loss of privacy in facilities. Tonight he cannot reliably communicate a consistent choice despite attempts at supported communication. There is no written directive about location of care. His wife is his documented health care proxy. She reports caregiver fatigue and asks about the small community inpatient hospice unit. A bed and ambulance are available only now. Transfer may provoke agitation or distress in an unfamiliar setting and limits privacy overnight. If he stays home, the hospice nurse can come within an hour and a comfort kit is in the home, but no overnight respite caregiver can arrive and his wife would need to manage symptoms between visits. Hospital policy and state law permit either plan based on surrogate consent. You must decide tonight.
data.choice_1: Arrange ambulance transfer and admit him to the inpatient hospice unit tonight
data.choice_2: Keep him at home overnight with hospice on-call support and symptom backup

choice_1.choice: Arrange ambulance transfer and admit him to the inpatient hospice unit tonight

choice_2.choice: Keep him at home overnight with hospice on-call support and symptom backup

value_clarity.suggested_changes: Add a clause stating the patient previously said he would accept inpatient hospice if his wife could no longer manage at home, or explicitly refused any facility transfer even if she was overwhelmed.

Add a clause stating the inpatient hospice unit can provide 24/7 nursing with rapid parenteral medications for worsening encephalopathy-related agitation, whereas at home there is a significant risk of prolonged uncontrolled agitation or dyspnea overnight if symptoms escalate.

data.vignette: A 68-year-old man with metastatic lung cancer is at home on hospice. He is newly jaundiced and bedbound. He is intermittently somnolent, and you suspect worsening hepatic encephalopathy from liver metastases. His pain is controlled on oral opioids. In prior visits he repeatedly said he wanted to die at home and feared loss of privacy in facilities. He also said he would accept inpatient hospice only if his wife could no longer safely manage his care at home. Tonight he cannot reliably communicate a consistent choice despite attempts at supported communication. There is no written directive about location of care. His wife is his documented health care proxy. She reports caregiver fatigue and asks about the local inpatient hospice unit. A bed and ambulance are available only now. The unit can provide 24/7 nursing and rapid parenteral medications if agitation or dyspnea worsens overnight. Transfer may provoke agitation or distress in an unfamiliar setting and limits privacy overnight. If he stays home, the hospice nurse can come within an hour and a comfort kit is in the home, but no overnight respite caregiver can arrive and his wife would need to manage symptoms between visits. Hospital policy and state law permit either plan based on surrogate consent. You must decide tonight.

choice_2.choice: Keep him at home overnight with hospice on-call support and symptom backup
